	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Emerging EP position broadly supportive of EC approach to 2013 CAP reforms </h1>

			
			<h4>
												21 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 25 May 2011, the European Parliament Agriculture Committee, in an own-initiative report, adopted the position that the EU agriculture budget needs to remain unchanged ‘in order to meet the challenges of food security, environmental protection and climate change’. This was reinforced on 10 June, when a resolution was adopted ‘which calls for agricultural funds to be at least maintained after 2013’.</p><p>These resolutions constitute an effort by the European Parliament to influence the all-important debate on the future level of CAP expenditures, on which proposals are expected in the coming months.</p><p>It is noted in press reports that ‘EU countries including France, Poland and the Netherlands have also called for the CAP budget to be kept at its present level, while the UK and Sweden want to see significant cuts in farm spending.’</p><p>The EP Agriculture Committee supported Commission proposals for the ‘greening’ of the CAP and ‘proposals to introduce a ceiling on direct payments per farmer and suggested that the size, the employment record and the degree of environmental protection of each farm should be taken into account when deciding on payments.’</p><p>On the role of financial speculation in agricultural markets, the Committee called for ‘a worldwide notification system to defend agricultural stocks intended for food security’, and endorsed recent French proposals tabled in the G20. The EC’s safety-net approach in dealing with crisis situations was also endorsed.</p><p>European farmers’ organisation Copa-Cogeca has welcomed both the Committee’s position, particularly as regards maintaining the two-pillar approach to the CAP ‘with food security remaining the main goal’, and the support of the Committee on ‘[strengthening] EU farmers’ position in the food chain to ensure that they get a better return from the market.’</p><p>The debate on the future of the CAP is taking place against a backdrop of rising EU prices. According to the EC’s May 2011 assessment, ‘for all the products, April 2011 prices were above the levels observed one year before: soft wheat (+98%); durum wheat (+69%); maize (+68%); barley (83%); SMP (+10%); butter (+31%); cheese (Edam) (+19%); beef (+8%); pork (+16%) and poultry meat (+19%).’ Indeed, April 2011 saw poultry prices reach the highest level in 14 years. However, elsewhere in April 2011 price rises were seen to be slowing down or – in the case of SMP, barley, butter and beef – falling marginally, compared to the previous month.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>EurActiv.com</i>, ‘EU lawmakers back CAP budget status quo’, 30 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.euractiv.com/en/cap/eu-lawmakers-back-cap-budget-status-quo-news-505153" target="_self">http://www.euractiv.com/en/cap/eu-lawmakers-back-cap-budget-status-quo-n...</a><br />
Copa-Cogeca, ‘Copa-Cogeca welcomes MEPs’ calls for strong CAP and strong EU budget in future, listed as 27 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en</a><br />
Copa-Cogeca, ‘Copa-Cogeca welcomes MEPs’ calls to at least maintain EU agriculture budget after 2013, and warns against any transfer of funds to other sectors’, 10 June 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en</a><br />
European Parliament Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development, ‘A new dawn for the CAP: Greener farming and more secure food supplies’, press release, 25 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.europarl.europa.eu/en/pressroom/content/20110523IPR19949/html/A-new-dawn-for-the-CAP-greener-farming-and-more-secure-food-supplies" target="_self">http://www.europarl.europa.eu/en/pressroom/content/20110523IPR19949/html...</a><br />
EC, ‘May 2011 update on recent agricultural commodity and food price developments in the EU’, Note to the file, Ref. LG D (2011) 618917, 20 May 2011<br />
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/markets/foodprices/food05_2011_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/markets/foodprices/food05_2011_...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The European Parliament position can be seen as broadly indicative of the widespread support in the majority of EU member states for the main proposals advanced by the EC for the further reform of the CAP (stable budget, fairer distribution of funds, greater emphasis on sustainability, the importance of strengthening the functioning of supply chains, and the critical importance of an effective safety-net policy to deal with price volatility).</p><p>From an ACP perspective, the issue of how precisely the EU’s safety-net policy will function is potentially of considerable importance. The use of expanded safety-net measures in the dairy sector in 2009 initially saw an expansion of skimmed-milk powder (SMP) in storage, and subsequently a major expansion of EU SMP exports in 2010. This trade in SMP is of concern to some ACP countries, since expanded EU exports can disrupt efforts to promote the better functioning of local milk farmer-to-dairy supply chains.</p><p>It should be noted that this is critically affected by the policy measures used and how precisely they are deployed (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/USDA-review-of-EU-dairy-sector-development" target="_blank">USDA review of EU dairy-sector development</a>’, July 2011). This is an increasingly important area for ACP–EU dialogue, if the implementation of EU safety-net measures is not simply to displace adjustment processes to third countries, including ACP countries. This raises the wider issue of ensuring that a reformed CAP is designed and managed in ways that minimise the adverse effects of EU policy measures on ACP agricultural economies.</p>
		</div>
		
